 ">full entry</a></span></span></span></div><div class="collapse" htag="div" hclass="collapse"><span class="unbox" id="apologetic_unbox_1" unbox="wordorigin"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">late Middle English (as a noun denoting a formal justification): from French <span class="ei">apologétique</span> or late Latin <span class="ei">apologeticus</span>, from Greek <span class="ei">apologētikos</span>, from <span class="ei">apologeisthei</span> ‘speak in one's own defence’, from <span class="ei">apologia</span>, from <span class="ei">apo</span> ‘away’+ <span class="ei">-logia</span> (see <span class="eb">-ology</span>). The current sense dates from the mid 19th cent.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
